## 2026-06-11 Architecture Review — AR4 (shared ServiceNow transport policy)
1. AR4 (P1 — two parallel SN clients): created a new built workspace package [`@syncrona/sn-transport`](packages/sn-transport) as the single source of truth for the transport-level policy that the two ServiceNow clients (core CLI on axios, MCP server on native fetch) must agree on but had copy-pasted. The package is intentionally pure (no I/O, no node globals).
2. AR4 scoped-prefix policy: extracted `DEFAULT_SCOPED_API_PREFIXES` (`x_nuvo_sinc`/`x_nuvo_sync`), `SCOPED_API_PREFIXES_ENV` (`SYNCRONA_SCOPED_API_PREFIXES`), `sanitizeScopedPrefix`, `parseConfiguredScopedApiPrefixes(rawEnvValue)` (parse the comma-separated override, fall back to defaults, de-dup), and `orderScopedApiPrefixes(configured, preferred?)` (preferred/last-successful first, then configured, de-dup) — the logic that was duplicated as `configuredEndpointPrefixes`/`endpointPrefixOrder` (core) vs `configuredScopedApiPrefixes`/`scopedPrefixOrder` (mcp).
3. AR4 retry policy: extracted the canonical retryable HTTP status set (`RETRYABLE_HTTP_STATUSES` = 408/425/429/500/502/503/504) and `shouldRetryStatus(status)`.
4. AR4 consumers: [packages/core/src/snClient.ts](packages/core/src/snClient.ts) now derives `endpointPrefixOrder()` from the shared helpers while keeping its own `cachedScopedEndpointPrefix` + the `getScopedEndpointPrefix()` export (consumed by `commandHelpers.ts` and asserted by tests). [packages/mcp-server/src/servicenowCore.ts](packages/mcp-server/src/servicenowCore.ts) dropped its local `RETRYABLE_STATUSES`/prefix constants/`sanitizeScopedPrefix`/`configuredScopedApiPrefixes`, imports the shared policy, re-exports `shouldRetryStatus` (still used internally and re-exported via `publicApi`), and reimplements `scopedPrefixOrder` on top of the shared helpers. Behavior is byte-for-byte identical in both.
